something like awk to convert FASTQ to FASTA, you'd use > to redirect the output. Here's the pattern:
awk 'NR%4==1{print ">"substr($0,2)} NR%4==2{print}' sample.fastq > sample.fasta 
for file in *.fastq; do
    awk 'NR%4==1{print ">"substr($0,2)} NR%4==2{print}' "$file" > "${file%.fastq}.fasta"
done
an explanation: 

> output_file — redirects stdout to a file
"${file%.fastq}.fasta" — strips the .fastq extension and replaces it with .fasta

e.g. sample1.fastq → sample1.fasta

How the FASTQ→FASTA conversion works (the awk part):

FASTQ files have 4 lines per read; FASTA only needs 2
NR%4==1 — grabs the header line (every 1st of 4 lines) and replaces @ with >
NR%4==2 — grabs the sequence line (every 2nd of 4 lines)
